<DOC><DOCNO> AP880907-0226 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0030EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-07 0554</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0579</SECOND><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The world's industrialized economies are boomingthis year, and governments should be ready to hit their economicbrakes if inflation shows signs of heating up, the InternationalMonetary Fund says.   The IMF outlook has been distributed to member governments butis not to be made public until later this month. A copy wasobtained and published Tuesday by the AP-Dow Jones News Service.   The fund's economists now anticipate inflation-adjusted growthof 3.8 percent for 1988, compared with the 2.8 percent increaseprojected in their April report.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Car and truck sales fell 10.7 percent in August,compared with the same month last year when incentives promptedquicker buying decisions by consumers, the automakers and analystssaid.   Foreign and domestic vehicle makers said they sold 1.25 millioncars and trucks last month, down from 1.35 million during the samemonth last year. Figures exclude Japan's Toyota Motor Sales USAInc. and South Korea's Hyundai Motor Co.   For the 10-day period ended Aug. 31, Chrysler Corp. said itssales of U.S.-made cars rose 2.6 percent compared with the sameperiod last year. Ford Motor Co. said its car sales for the periodfell 1.4 percent and General Motors Corp. reported a 13.9 percentdrop.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oil futures prices have slid to a nearlytwo-year low as traders continued to lose confidence in OPEC'sability to restrain its production.   On the New York Mercantile Exchange on Tuesday, futurescontracts for October delivery of West Texas Intermediate, thebenchmark grade of U.S. crude, dropped 55 cents a barrel to $14.24.   Crude prices have not closed that low on the exchange sinceOctober 1986, when they reached $13.73 per barrel.</TEXT><DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   This year's summer movies shattered box-officerecords with roughly $1.7 billion in tickets sold, up from lastyear's summer record of $1.59 billion.   ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' got the headlines but it was apair of comedies featuring a cartoon bunny and a prince in searchof a bride that led the way.   The biggest hits were ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' ``Coming toAmerica,'' ```Crocodile' Dundee II'' and ``Big.''</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   IBM's top rivals in personal computers havecalled a news conference for next Tuesday at which they areexpected to announce an alternative design for the way informationflows inside a personal computer.   The new design would make it possible for the companies to buildpersonal computers that rival IBM's 1{-year-old Personal System-2line without departing so far from the older standard, analystssaid Tuesday.   Compaq Computer Corp. of Houston is leading the challenge, whichmay eventually include as many as 30 companies that make personalcomputers or related products, said Jim Weil, an analyst forGartner Securities Corp.</TEXT><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Attorneys for Eastern Airlines' unions have learnedthey will return to federal court later this month to argue theircase against the elimination of 4,000 jobs.   The U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington told Eastern on Tuesdayto submit legal briefs on its position by Sept. 12.   While attorneys for the Machinists and Air Line PilotsAssociation unions had not fully decided on their next move,options included seeking a temporary injunction from the U.S.Supreme Court against the layoffs.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>